@Valeria V 
Great response! I also noticed many of the points given. 
One of your questions was how you wonder why there are more fast food workers than registered nurses / more customer service representatives than nursing assistants. In my opinion, I think this may be due to the fact that there are more requirements in order to become a nurse, rather than the other jobs, making more people go for easier more accessible jobs. Do you think this may be a reason why there are more workers in fast food or customer service compared to nurses?

@Jaylee Thanks for submitting a comment to WGOITG. What about the graph made you decide there are a lot of essential people?  Are there more essential workers or frontline workers? As far as frontline, I think part of it is not just working with people, but also the fact that the job can't be done from home.  Transportation workers like truck drivers or bus drivers can't work from home. With this graph representing 70% of workers, it is leaving off some people who need the vaccine, but aren't workers.  

And the graph doesn't really show priority.  To read about the factors that states may consider to determine the priority for getting the vaccine, you may want to read this other New York Times article "People Are Dying.  Whom Do We Save First With the Vaccine?" (Jan. 3, 2021).  Here a panel of public health experts give different criteria for deciding the order of vaccination. 

Be sure to return for the reveal to learn more about the news story that accompanied this graph.

@Yomi Thank you for your thoughtful comments for WGOITG. I agree that there are more frontline than essential workers.  What about the graph made you make this decision?  When you move your mouse across the dots you can see the various individual jobs and I also wondered about the postsecondary chemistry teachers. 

To read about the factors that states may consider to determine the priority for getting the vaccine, you may want to read this other New York Times article "People Are Dying.  Whom Do We Save First With the Vaccine?" (Jan. 3, 2021).  Different states also can prioritize who gets the vaccine in slightly different ways.  I encourage you to research what your state is doing for vaccination priority.

Thanks for sharing a catchy headline.

@Lauren Iskander Thanks for sharing your thoughts. You have some good observations. As you look at the frontline workers think about what work must be done at the workplace and in front of people versus what work could possibly be done online or from home.  And does this graph possibly show who should get vaccinated first?

It is good to hear that many people you know that are "frontline" have received the vaccine or plan on getting it soon.

Be sure to check out the reveal once it is posted.

@Angel Thanks for posting a comment.  Under the graph it says 70% of workers are essential and that includes frontline essential.  With about 150 milion U.S. workers, how many do you estimate as being frontline essential? And how long do you think it might take to vaccinate that many people?

To decide if an occupation is frontline essential or just essential and not frontline, think about the work taht is done.  For example,can the work be done from home or not?

Do you have a catchy headline that could accompany this graph?

@joshua laine I notice that there are about 4 million Fast-Food and counter workers which is almost surprising but it does make sense that Food preparation and serving would be an essential business. 

I also feel like healthcare workers and workers that are constantly exposed to the virus and constantly put their healthcare at risk should get vaccinated first.

The impact this information presented has on me really was just a wake up call because I personally work in the Fast-Food industry and my mother is a nurse so it's very informing to know the demand for my job in this pandemic may just be essential.

